WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.663
Most AI mistakes begin before the prompt: we choose the wrong

2
00:00:03.663 --> 00:00:05.357
relationship with the system.

3
00:00:05.307 --> 00:00:09.241
We ask when we need a working session, keep chatting when execution is

4
00:00:09.241 --> 00:00:12.557
ready, or delegate work whose destination is still unclear.

5
00:00:12.557 --> 00:00:16.586
The useful question is not, “How autonomous can this AI become?

6
00:00:16.586 --> 00:00:20.641
Ask instead: “What human attention does this task need, and how much

7
00:00:20.641 --> 00:00:22.788
execution can the agent safely take?

8
00:00:22.788 --> 00:00:24.903
Those are separate decisions.

9
00:00:24.903 --> 00:00:29.618
Microsoft's 2026 Work Trend Index describes four modes: asking,

10
00:00:29.618 --> 00:00:32.836
collaboration, exploration, and delegation.

11
00:00:32.836 --> 00:00:34.951
They are not a maturity ladder.

12
00:00:34.951 --> 00:00:37.480
Each fits different task conditions.

13
00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:41.629
We will build a practical four-mode map: when to use each mode, what to

14
00:00:41.629 --> 00:00:44.201
hand over, what to keep, and when to switch.

15
00:00:44.201 --> 00:00:46.692
You can use it before your next prompt.

16
00:00:46.692 --> 00:00:51.227
Keep one principle in view: execution can move to an agent, but outcome

17
00:00:51.227 --> 00:00:52.951
responsibility stays human.

18
00:00:52.951 --> 00:00:55.750
A good workflow makes that boundary clearer.

19
00:00:55.900 --> 00:00:58.465
Start with two independent axes.

20
00:00:58.415 --> 00:01:02.305
Human intensity measures how much continuous judgment, taste,

21
00:01:02.305 --> 00:01:05.175
negotiation, or context only you can provide.

22
00:01:05.175 --> 00:01:09.738
Agent intensity measures how much searching, transforming, coordinating,

23
00:01:09.738 --> 00:01:11.703
or tool use the AI can perform.

24
00:01:11.703 --> 00:01:13.992
These axes are not opposites.

25
00:01:13.992 --> 00:01:18.459
A task can require high human intensity and high agent intensity at the

26
00:01:18.459 --> 00:01:19.088
same time.

27
00:01:19.088 --> 00:01:23.288
A product launch, for example, may need constant human calls while an

28
00:01:23.288 --> 00:01:27.367
agent gathers evidence, updates artifacts, and checks dependencies.

29
00:01:27.367 --> 00:01:29.800
Now add four routing questions.

30
00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:32.434
Is the desired output already specific?

31
00:01:32.434 --> 00:01:35.559
How much human judgment must stay inside the work?

32
00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:38.482
Can success be checked with observable evidence?

33
00:01:38.482 --> 00:01:40.925
And what happens if the AI is wrong?

34
00:01:40.925 --> 00:01:45.059
Those questions are more useful than asking whether a model is capable.

35
00:01:45.059 --> 00:01:47.501
Capability is only one input.

36
00:01:47.501 --> 00:01:51.662
A capable model can still be a poor fit when the task is ambiguous, the

37
00:01:51.662 --> 00:01:54.886
evidence is weak, or a mistake has a large consequence.

38
00:01:54.886 --> 00:01:58.309
The Microsoft research makes the human boundary visible.

39
00:01:58.309 --> 00:02:02.204
Eighty-six percent of respondents treated AI output as a starting point

40
00:02:02.204 --> 00:02:05.550
and still saw themselves as responsible for the final result.

41
00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:08.319
The important move is not removing the human.

42
00:02:08.319 --> 00:02:11.742
It is placing human attention where it changes the outcome.

43
00:02:11.742 --> 00:02:14.473
So draw the map before you choose the tool.

44
00:02:14.473 --> 00:02:18.742
Put human intensity on one axis, agent intensity on the other, and route

45
00:02:18.742 --> 00:02:20.521
the current phase of the task.

46
00:02:20.521 --> 00:02:24.467
Do not label an entire project once and assume the mode will never

47
00:02:24.467 --> 00:02:24.886
change.

48
00:02:24.886 --> 00:02:29.059
First, Human intensity and agent intensity are independent.

49
00:02:29.059 --> 00:02:33.021
Second, Choose from task conditions, not AI ambition.

50
00:02:33.021 --> 00:02:36.050
Third, Outcome ownership stays with the human.

51
00:02:36.172 --> 00:02:40.372
Use asking mode when one bounded uncertainty blocks a human decision.

52
00:02:40.322 --> 00:02:42.581
You are not handing over the work.

53
00:02:42.581 --> 00:02:47.347
You are buying clarity: a definition, a comparison, a counterexample, a

54
00:02:47.347 --> 00:02:49.764
calculation, or a short explanation.

55
00:02:49.764 --> 00:02:53.033
A strong question includes the decision it will support.

56
00:02:53.033 --> 00:02:56.564
Instead of asking, “What are good onboarding patterns?” ask, “Which

57
00:02:56.564 --> 00:03:00.147
onboarding pattern best fits a mobile tool with one core action, and

58
00:03:00.147 --> 00:03:02.466
what failure signal would make us reject it?

59
00:03:02.466 --> 00:03:05.447
The output should stay small enough to inspect.

60
00:03:05.447 --> 00:03:09.741
Ask for assumptions, confidence boundaries, or the evidence behind a

61
00:03:09.741 --> 00:03:10.120
claim.

62
00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:14.050
If the answer cannot be checked, it should not silently become a premise

63
00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:15.033
for the next step.

64
00:03:15.033 --> 00:03:18.168
Asking mode is also useful during live work.

65
00:03:18.168 --> 00:03:21.910
A developer can ask for the meaning of an error, a writer can ask for

66
00:03:21.910 --> 00:03:25.489
three alternative framings, and a manager can ask which constraint

67
00:03:25.489 --> 00:03:27.062
creates the biggest tradeoff.

68
00:03:27.062 --> 00:03:29.322
The human remains the operator.

69
00:03:29.322 --> 00:03:31.947
The common failure is question drift.

70
00:03:31.947 --> 00:03:36.239
A simple request expands into a plan, then into generated artifacts,

71
00:03:36.239 --> 00:03:39.206
then into actions nobody explicitly authorized.

72
00:03:39.206 --> 00:03:41.023
Stop the expansion.

73
00:03:41.023 --> 00:03:45.257
If execution becomes the real need, switch modes deliberately and define

74
00:03:45.257 --> 00:03:46.139
a new boundary.

75
00:03:46.139 --> 00:03:48.533
The exit condition is a decision.

76
00:03:48.533 --> 00:03:52.836
Once the uncertainty is removed, return to the human task or move into

77
00:03:52.836 --> 00:03:53.697
collaboration.

78
00:03:53.697 --> 00:03:57.799
Endless follow-up questions often mean the problem is no longer a single

79
00:03:57.799 --> 00:03:58.312
question.

80
00:03:58.312 --> 00:04:01.620
First, Ask to remove one bounded uncertainty.

81
00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:04.735
Second, Keep the question tied to a decision.

82
00:04:04.735 --> 00:04:08.072
Third, Verify answers before they shape action.

83
00:04:08.212 --> 00:04:12.263
Use collaboration mode when the destination matters, but the route needs

84
00:04:12.263 --> 00:04:13.613
repeated human judgment.

85
00:04:13.563 --> 00:04:15.592
Both sides stay active.

86
00:04:15.592 --> 00:04:20.423
The AI proposes, transforms, or checks; the human selects, redirects,

87
00:04:20.423 --> 00:04:23.573
and supplies context the system cannot infer.

88
00:04:23.573 --> 00:04:26.833
Collaboration works best around a shared artifact.

89
00:04:26.833 --> 00:04:31.044
Edit the actual brief, code path, model, or storyboard.

90
00:04:31.044 --> 00:04:35.021
A concrete artifact turns taste into visible decisions and prevents the

91
00:04:35.021 --> 00:04:38.438
conversation from becoming an abstract stream of suggestions.

92
00:04:38.438 --> 00:04:40.237
Work in short loops.

93
00:04:40.237 --> 00:04:44.309
Ask for one meaningful change, inspect the result, and state what

94
00:04:44.309 --> 00:04:45.499
improved or failed.

95
00:04:45.499 --> 00:04:49.032
The next instruction should update the artifact and the acceptance

96
00:04:49.032 --> 00:04:52.083
criteria, not restart the whole task from a blank prompt.

97
00:04:52.083 --> 00:04:56.617
This mode is powerful for writing, design, diagnosis, planning, and code

98
00:04:56.617 --> 00:04:59.640
review because quality emerges through contrast.

99
00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:03.296
The AI can generate options quickly, but the human decides which

100
00:05:03.296 --> 00:05:05.410
tradeoff belongs in the final result.

101
00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:08.323
The common failure is invisible convergence.

102
00:05:08.323 --> 00:05:13.006
The conversation feels productive, yet nobody can say what “done” means.

103
00:05:13.006 --> 00:05:17.307
Keep a small scorecard: audience, purpose, constraints, must-keep facts,

104
00:05:17.307 --> 00:05:21.131
and the test that determines whether the artifact is acceptable.

105
00:05:21.131 --> 00:05:25.256
Collaboration ends when the next steps become mechanical and checkable.

106
00:05:25.256 --> 00:05:28.833
At that point, package the remaining work for delegation.

107
00:05:28.833 --> 00:05:33.265
If the artifact still has competing directions, stay in collaboration or

108
00:05:33.265 --> 00:05:35.112
move briefly into exploration.

109
00:05:35.112 --> 00:05:39.102
First, Collaborate when judgment improves every iteration.

110
00:05:39.102 --> 00:05:42.967
Second, Share a live artifact instead of abstract chat.

111
00:05:42.967 --> 00:05:45.919
Third, Keep acceptance criteria visible.

112
00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:50.029
Use exploration mode when the destination itself is unstable.

113
00:05:49.979 --> 00:05:53.997
You may not know which problem matters, which explanation is true, or

114
00:05:53.997 --> 00:05:56.094
which opportunity is worth pursuing.

115
00:05:56.094 --> 00:05:58.556
The goal is not immediate production.

116
00:05:58.556 --> 00:06:00.719
The goal is to improve the map.

117
00:06:00.719 --> 00:06:03.835
Ask the AI to widen and structure the space.

118
00:06:03.835 --> 00:06:08.350
Generate competing hypotheses, search for disconfirming evidence, group

119
00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:11.911
unknowns, compare user segments, or reveal dependencies.

120
00:06:11.911 --> 00:06:15.998
Good exploration produces contrasts, not just a longer list.

121
00:06:15.998 --> 00:06:19.902
Human intensity remains high because relevance is contextual.

122
00:06:19.902 --> 00:06:23.664
The agent can surface patterns, but you decide which signals matter,

123
00:06:23.664 --> 00:06:27.536
which sources are credible, and which question deserves the next hour.

124
00:06:27.536 --> 00:06:30.498
Curiosity is guided, not outsourced.

125
00:06:30.498 --> 00:06:34.098
Use an evidence board with four columns: what we think, what we

126
00:06:34.098 --> 00:06:37.527
observed, what would change our mind, and what we will test.

127
00:06:37.527 --> 00:06:41.392
This keeps generated possibilities separate from verified facts and

128
00:06:41.392 --> 00:06:42.892
makes uncertainty visible.

129
00:06:42.892 --> 00:06:45.700
The common failure is possibility theater.

130
00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:49.680
More ideas create the feeling of progress while commitment keeps moving

131
00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:49.960
away.

132
00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:54.396
Set a budget for time, sources, or experiments, and name the decision

133
00:06:54.396 --> 00:06:56.325
that exploration must support.

134
00:06:56.325 --> 00:07:00.717
Exploration should end with a narrower question, a selected direction,

135
00:07:00.717 --> 00:07:01.344
or a test.

136
00:07:01.344 --> 00:07:05.387
Then switch to asking for one missing fact, collaboration for shaping

137
00:07:05.387 --> 00:07:08.258
the solution, or delegation for running the test.

138
00:07:08.258 --> 00:07:11.690
First, Explore before the destination is stable.

139
00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:16.027
Second, Generate contrasts, evidence, and better questions.

140
00:07:16.027 --> 00:07:18.895
Third, End exploration with a decision.

141
00:07:19.012 --> 00:07:22.813
Use delegation mode when the outcome is specific, the steps can be

142
00:07:22.813 --> 00:07:26.154
executed with available tools, and success can be checked.

143
00:07:26.104 --> 00:07:30.439
The human defines the task package; the agent runs the work and returns

144
00:07:30.439 --> 00:07:30.988
evidence.

145
00:07:30.988 --> 00:07:35.102
A useful delegation packet has six parts: the desired outcome, the

146
00:07:35.102 --> 00:07:39.528
relevant context, hard constraints, allowed tools, stop conditions, and

147
00:07:39.528 --> 00:07:41.585
the evidence required at handoff.

148
00:07:41.585 --> 00:07:45.094
Missing any one of these creates hidden interpretation work.

149
00:07:45.094 --> 00:07:48.219
Give the agent authority that matches the consequence.

150
00:07:48.219 --> 00:07:52.796
Reading files, drafting a report, or running tests may be reversible.

151
00:07:52.796 --> 00:07:57.208
Publishing, spending money, deleting data, or messaging people needs

152
00:07:57.208 --> 00:07:58.181
explicit gates.

153
00:07:58.181 --> 00:08:01.787
Autonomy is scoped permission, not a personality trait.

154
00:08:01.787 --> 00:08:04.056
Require observable evidence.

155
00:08:04.056 --> 00:08:07.815
A code task returns the changed files and test results.

156
00:08:07.815 --> 00:08:12.229
A research task returns primary sources and unresolved uncertainty.

157
00:08:12.229 --> 00:08:16.915
A publishing task returns the public URL, visibility state, and channel

158
00:08:16.915 --> 00:08:17.575
placement.

159
00:08:17.575 --> 00:08:21.335
The common failure is reviewing the narration instead of the result.

160
00:08:21.335 --> 00:08:25.075
An agent can sound confident while the artifact is incomplete.

161
00:08:25.075 --> 00:08:28.960
Inspect the output, the checks, and the boundary conditions.

162
00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:31.094
Confidence is not evidence.

163
00:08:31.094 --> 00:08:35.296
Delegation ends with acceptance, rejection, or a mode switch.

164
00:08:35.296 --> 00:08:39.361
If the agent finds an ambiguous requirement, bring the task back to

165
00:08:39.361 --> 00:08:40.210
collaboration.

166
00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:43.767
If it finds an unknown problem, move to exploration.

167
00:08:43.767 --> 00:08:46.363
A good stop is part of a good handoff.

168
00:08:46.363 --> 00:08:49.854
First, Delegate only a specified task package.

169
00:08:49.854 --> 00:08:54.796
Second, Give tools, constraints, stop conditions, and evidence.

170
00:08:54.796 --> 00:08:58.469
Third, Review the outcome, not the agent's confidence.

171
00:08:58.588 --> 00:09:01.201
Real work rarely stays in one mode.

172
00:09:01.151 --> 00:09:04.690
A project may begin with exploration, use asking to remove one

173
00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:08.686
uncertainty, move into collaboration to shape the artifact, and finish

174
00:09:08.686 --> 00:09:11.026
with delegation for repeatable execution.

175
00:09:11.026 --> 00:09:14.911
Start with the least autonomous mode that can produce the next useful

176
00:09:14.911 --> 00:09:15.305
result.

177
00:09:15.305 --> 00:09:17.622
This is not fear of automation.

178
00:09:17.622 --> 00:09:21.632
It is a way to learn the task boundary before expanding execution.

179
00:09:21.632 --> 00:09:23.843
Evidence earns more autonomy.

180
00:09:23.843 --> 00:09:25.968
Use four switch signals.

181
00:09:25.968 --> 00:09:29.669
Switch when the desired output becomes clearer, when a judgment call

182
00:09:29.669 --> 00:09:33.533
appears, when evidence contradicts the plan, or when the consequence of

183
00:09:33.533 --> 00:09:34.295
error changes.

184
00:09:34.295 --> 00:09:37.567
Each signal changes the proper human-agent balance.

185
00:09:37.567 --> 00:09:40.074
Imagine preparing a customer launch.

186
00:09:40.074 --> 00:09:42.449
Explore the audience and risks.

187
00:09:42.449 --> 00:09:44.795
Ask for one missing comparison.

188
00:09:44.795 --> 00:09:48.093
Collaborate on the positioning and acceptance criteria.

189
00:09:48.093 --> 00:09:51.372
Delegate the asset checks and scheduled publication.

190
00:09:51.372 --> 00:09:54.372
Then return to human review at the release gate.

191
00:09:54.372 --> 00:09:58.975
Record each handoff in one line: current mode, next result, owner,

192
00:09:58.975 --> 00:10:00.997
evidence, and stop condition.

193
00:10:00.997 --> 00:10:05.369
That tiny log prevents silent expansion and makes recovery easier when a

194
00:10:05.369 --> 00:10:06.584
task is interrupted.

195
00:10:06.584 --> 00:10:10.776
The loop is simple: choose, run, inspect, and reroute.

196
00:10:10.776 --> 00:10:13.834
Do not reward an agent for staying autonomous.

197
00:10:13.834 --> 00:10:18.041
Reward the workflow for producing a correct, useful, and accountable

198
00:10:18.041 --> 00:10:18.536
outcome.

199
00:10:18.536 --> 00:10:22.199
First, Start with the least autonomous mode that can work.

200
00:10:22.199 --> 00:10:26.045
Second, Switch when uncertainty or consequence changes.

201
00:10:26.045 --> 00:10:29.449
Third, Record evidence before expanding autonomy.

202
00:10:29.572 --> 00:10:32.820
The four-mode map is not a taxonomy to memorize.

203
00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:34.491
It is a routing tool.

204
00:10:34.491 --> 00:10:38.459
Before the next prompt, identify the uncertainty, the judgment you must

205
00:10:38.459 --> 00:10:42.482
keep, the execution the agent can take, and the evidence that will prove

206
00:10:42.482 --> 00:10:43.097
the result.

207
00:10:43.097 --> 00:10:46.847
First, Separate human intensity from agent intensity.

208
00:10:46.847 --> 00:10:51.097
Second, Match the mode to uncertainty, judgment, and risk.

209
00:10:51.097 --> 00:10:54.542
Third, Switch deliberately and keep outcome ownership.

210
00:10:54.542 --> 00:10:58.613
Use asking for one bounded uncertainty, collaboration for iterative

211
00:10:58.613 --> 00:11:02.805
judgment, exploration for an unstable destination, and delegation for

212
00:11:02.805 --> 00:11:04.020
specified execution.

213
00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:07.318
If the task changes, the mode should change with it.

214
00:11:07.318 --> 00:11:11.292
Following practical AI and agent work methods matters because the models

215
00:11:11.292 --> 00:11:14.824
will keep changing, while the need to define intent, boundaries,

216
00:11:14.824 --> 00:11:17.087
evidence, and responsibility will remain.

217
00:11:17.087 --> 00:11:21.058
Those skills let you use stronger systems without giving up judgment.

218
00:11:21.058 --> 00:11:25.213
On your next task, draw the two axes, choose the smallest useful mode,

219
00:11:25.213 --> 00:11:27.943
and write the stop condition before you begin.

220
00:11:27.943 --> 00:11:32.144
That is how an AI workflow becomes more capable and more trustworthy at

221
00:11:32.144 --> 00:11:32.972
the same time.
